article.headline: Raptors a game below .500 going into break
article.linkText: Allen, Lewis lead Sonics past Raptors
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle coach Nate McMillan is still holding out hope that his team can avoid the lottery for the second straight season. With Ray Allen scoring 23 points and Rashard Lewis adding 22 points and nine rebounds, the Sonics finished the first half of their season in impressive fashion with a 94-74 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Thursday night. "It's been an up-and-down season," McMillan said. "It's been a season of a lot of strange games. What we want to do this second half is play consistent basketball and do the things we need to do." Losers of seven of their previous nine games, the Sonics got nine assists from starting point guard Antonio Daniels and a career-high eight assists from rookie Luke Ridnour in finishing with a 25-27 record before the All-Star break. McMillan said the Sonics need to play the kind of defense they played against the Raptors if they're going to have a chance to make the playoffs. "I thought defensively we were solid tonight," he said. "We kept the ball in front of us." Allen, the Sonics' best player, agreed. "We played defense tonight," he said. "We rotated and stayed together as a team. That's the biggest key. Offensively, we can go one-on-one every time down the floor." The Sonics were without Allen, a four-time All-Star, for the first 25 games this season after he underwent surgery to his right ankle. And they're currently without starting point guard Brent Barry for five to six weeks with a broken ring finger on his right hand. "It's been a tough road the last two weeks," McMillan said. "One thing I told the team, though, is that tough times don't last." Allen is playing with a painful sprained left shoulder that he hopes will be all healed by the time the Sonics play next Thursday night at home against Philadelphia. "My shoulder is bothering me," he said. "I lose a little bit of confidence in my shoulder because I can't do things I normally would be capable of. It's almost like I limp down the court." The Raptors, who had a three-game road winning streak snapped, wound up at 25-26 before the break. In a matchup of small forwards, Carter went up against Lewis. Lewis was the winner. "My job was to keep him out of the paint because he's so tough to guard around the rim," Lewis said. "I was just pretty much trying to be aggressive." Alvin Williams led the Raptors with a season-high 20 points, Vince Carter had 19 on 8-for-21 shooting, and Donyell Marshall added 16 points and 17 rebounds. Morris Peterson had 10 rebounds. Chris Bosh, Toronto's 19-year-old rookie starting center, played only one minute of the second half before he came out because of the aftereffects of a sprained left ankle that caused him to miss three games. Bosh didn't score a point and had three rebounds in 14 minutes. He returned to the lineup and played 28 minutes Tuesday night in Phoenix. Bosh is supposed to take part in the All-Star weekend in Los Angeles, but Toronto coach Kevin O'Neill doesn't think that will happen. Bosh is on the rookie roster to face the league's second-year All-Stars Friday night. "I would assume that he won't be playing in the rookie game," McNeill said. "He probably won't be able to play." But Bosh said he wants to go to Los Angeles and give his ankle a try. "I'm a player and I want to play every day," he said. "If it's up to me, I'm going to play." With Bosh sitting on the bench and looking dejected, the Sonics led by 17 points as many as four times in the third quarter when they went ahead 70-55 at the end of the period.< ^Notes: Bosh had an exceptional block of a driving fast-break dunk attempt by Ronald Murray late in the first quarter. Bosh was averaging 1.42 blocks, 27th in the NBA, coming into the game. ... Double technicals were whistled against Seattle's Vladimir Radmanovich and Toronto's Michael Curry when they got tangled up early in the final quarter.
